        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 pt-3 pr-3"><em>Stormwater, the water that runs off impervious surfaces during rainfall, is a critical element in urban environments. 
          While seemingly benign, its journey through our cities can transform it into a potent source of pollution, significantly impacting Nigeria&#8217;s ecosystems and public health.</em>
        </p>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 pt-2 pr-3"><em>Effective quality control (QC) for drainage systems is paramount to preventing stormwater pollution and ensuring urban water safety. 
          This article delves into the environmental ramifications of polluted runoff, examines Nigeria&#8217;s environmental regulations, and outlines essential QC measures for stormwater management Nigeria.</em>
        </p>
        <img src="images/preventimg2.jpg" alt="preventimg2"/>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 mt-1 pr-3"><em><u>Inspection of Levant Nig. Ltd Stormwater channel <br> construction through Ogbe-Ijaw Market, Warri</u></em></p>
        <hr>
        <h4 class="text-decoration-underline text-light text-center"><strong><em>The Environmental Impacts Of Polluted <br> Stormwater Runoff In Nigeria</em></strong></h4>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 pt-2 pr-3"><em>The consequences of untreated stormwater pollution in Nigeria are severe and far-reaching. Critical impacts include:</em></p>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
            <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong><u>Sedimentation:</u></strong></em> <br>
                <em>Eroded soil from construction sites and bare land is washed into waterways, leading to sedimentation. This process clouds water bodies, suffocates aquatic habitats by smothering benthic organisms, and reduces light penetration, hindering plant growth.</em>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong><u>Nutrient Overload:</u></strong></em> <br>
            <em> Runoff often carries fertilizers, pet waste, and decaying organic matter, introducing excess nutrients like nitrogen and phosphorus into rivers and lakes. This overload can trigger harmful algal blooms, which deplete dissolved oxygen in the water, leading to fish kills and posing human health hazards through toxins produced by some algae.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong><u>Toxic Contamination:</u></strong></em> <br>
            <em> Urban runoff is a notorious carrier of hazardous substances. Studies have revealed that pollutants from activities like automobile workshops, such as heavy metals (lead, cadmium) and oils, can exceed Nigerian and even US EPA (Environmental Protection Agency) standards by a staggering 200-300% [1][6]. These chemicals are toxic to aquatic life and can bioaccumulate in the food chain, eventually impacting human health.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<strong><u><em>Pathogen Spread:</em></u></strong> <br> 
            <em> Runoff can pick up bacteria and viruses from contaminated surfaces, including animal waste and sewage leaks. This can lead to widespread waterborne diseases, such as cholera and typhoid, and can result in the closure of recreational beaches and bathing waters, severely impacting public health and local economies [2].</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
