        <h4 class="text-decoration-underline text-light text-center"><strong><em>Regulatory Framework Governing Stormwater Pollution In Nigeria</em></strong></h4>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 pt-2 pr-3"><em>Nigeria has established a legal framework to address stormwater pollution and enforce water pollution prevention. Key legislation includes:</em></p>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong>The National Environmental Standards and Regulations Enforcement Agency (NESREA) Act (2007):</strong></em> <br>
            <em> This act is the cornerstone of environmental protection in Nigeria. It explicitly prohibits the discharge of hazardous substances into the environment, 
             with significant penalties.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul>
              <li><em><strong>Section 27:</strong> Prohibits the discharge of hazardous substances, carrying fines of up to ₦1 million and potential imprisonment for up to 5 years [3][4].</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul>
              <li><em><strong>Section 8:</strong> Mandates effluent limitation regulations for industries, requiring them to treat their wastewater before discharge [3].</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong><u>The Water Resources Act:</u></strong></em> <br>
            <em> This legislation governs the use and management of water resources and mandates that any entity wishing to discharge pollutants into water bodies must obtain a consent from the relevant authorities.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light pr-4 pl-4">
          <li><i>▪</i>&ensp;<em><strong><u>State-level Environmental Laws:</u></strong></em> <br>
            <em> Many states have enacted their own environmental protection laws that complement federal regulations. For instance, Lagos State imposes fines of ₦500,000 for the discharge of untreated waste into drainage systems [3].</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>These regulations underscore Nigeria&#8217;s commitment to environmental protection and the need for robust drainage system quality control to ensure compliance.</em></p>
