        <h4 class="text-decoration-underline text-light text-center"><em><strong>Quality Control Measures For <br> Pollution Mitigation</strong></em></h4>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 pt-2 pr-3"><em>Effective quality control (QC) in drainage systems requires a multi-faceted approach, encompassing planning, construction, and post-construction phases. The goal is to minimize pollutant loads entering waterways.</em></p>
        <h4 class="text-light text-start pl-4"><em>1.&ensp; <u>Pre-Construction Planning</u></em></h4>
        <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>&ensp;Thorough planning is the first line of defense against <strong>stormwater pollution</strong>.</em></p>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><strong><u>Site-Specific Design:</u></strong>&ensp; Drainage systems must be designed based on detailed, site-specific design principles. This involves accurately
                calculating drainage capacity using local rainfall data and considering future climate projections for rainfall intensity and frequency [5]. This ensures 
                that the system can handle expected runoff volumes without overwhelming its capacity, which can lead to bypass of treatment measures.</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><strong><u>Material Selection:</u></strong>&ensp;The choice of materials for drainage infrastructure is critical. Civil engineering professionals must select
               corrosion-resistant, high-strength materials that are durable and less likely to degrade and leach pollutants into the stormwater. Material selection 
               should be validated through laboratory testing to ensure compliance with performance and environmental standards [5].</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <img src="images/preventImg5.jpg" alt="preventImg5"/>
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 mt-1 pr-3"><em><u>Pre - construction planning</u></em></p>
        <hr>
        <h4 class="text-light text-start pl-4"><em>2.&ensp; <u>Construction Phase Controls</u></em></h4>
        <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em> &ensp;During the construction phase, implementing robust stormwater pollution control measures is essential to prevent
          sediment and other pollutants from escaping the site.</em>
        </p>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Erosion And Sediment Control (ESC):</u>&ensp; This is a crucial aspect of preventing stormwater pollution at the source. 
                Common ESC measures include:</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Sediment Basins:</u>&ensp; These temporary structures are designed to trap eroded soil and sediment by slowing down runoff and allowing 
                solids to settle out before the water is discharged [5]. They should be installed upstream of drainage inlets and outfalls.</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Gravel Filters:</u>&ensp; Placing a layer of gravel filters (typically 20-40mm sized gravel) at the entrance of drainage inlets <br> can effectively capture
                 coarse pollutants and larger <br> sediment particles [5].</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Bio-retention Zones:</u>&ensp; Establishing bio-retention zones <br> or rain gardens planted with native vegetation along drainage channels
                 can help absorb nutrients and filter pollutants through natural processes [5]. These are particularly effective for rainwater runoff safety.</em>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-center lead text-light"><img style="width: 90%; height: 90%;" src="images/preventImg6.png" alt="preventImg6"/><br><em><u>Construction Phase Controls Table</u></em></p>
        <hr>
        <h4 class="text-light text-start pl-4"><em>3.&ensp; <u>Post-Construction Solutions</u></em></h4>
        <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em> &ensp;Once the drainage system is operational, ongoing QC and maintenance are vital.</em></p>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-2">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Modular Filtration Systems:</u>&ensp; For ongoing stormwater management Nigeria, the use of modular filtration systems offers a promising solution. These systems can combine various natural and engineered materials for multi-stage treatment. For example, trials in Nigeria have demonstrated that systems incorporating rice husk (for organic pollutant removal), activated carbon (for chemical adsorption), and river gravel (for sediment capture) can achieve up to 85% pollutant reduction [6]. These are examples of pollution prevention techniques.</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <img src="images/preventIMg7.jpg" alt="preventIMg7">
        <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 mt-1 pr-3"><em><u>Construction Phase Controls</u></em></p>
        <hr>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-3">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Maintenance Protocols:</u>&ensp; A proactive maintenance schedule is crucial for sustained system performance and drainage system maintenance Nigeria.</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-3">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Quarterly Drain Cleaning:</u>&ensp; Regular cleaning of drainage channels and pipes is essential to prevent blockages caused by debris and sediment, which can lead to localized flooding and reduced system efficiency [5].</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="lead text-light">
          <li style="list-style-type: none">
            <ul class="pl-2 pr-3">
              <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Biannual Water Quality Testing:</u>&ensp; Periodic testing of discharged water for key pollutants like heavy metals and oils helps monitor the effectiveness of control measures and identify potential issues early [6]. This aligns with easy tips for drainage quality.</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul> 
