              <h4 class="text-light mt-3 text-start pl-4"><em>4.&ensp; <u>Innovative Localized Treatments</u></em></h4>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>Addressing pollution at its source is often the most effective strategy.</em></p>
              <ul class="lead text-light">
                <li style="list-style-type: none">
                    <ul class="pl-2 pr-3">
                      <li><i>▪</i>&emsp;<em><u>Automobile Workshop Filters:</u>&ensp; Many automobile workshops, critical for the transport sector, are significant sources of oil, grease, and heavy metal pollution. Implementing custom Low Impact Development (LID) systems, such as filters using readily available agricultural waste like rice husk, can effectively treat this oil and grease-laden runoff directly at the source. This proactive approach is key to how to reduce urban water pollution [1][6].</em>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <img src="images/preventImg10.jpg" alt="preventIMg10">
              <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 mt-1 pr-3"><em><u>Innovative Localized Treatments</u></em></p>
              <hr>
              <h4 class="text-center text-decoration-underline text-light" ><em>Are There Specific Trends In Stormwater <br> Pollution That Nigeria Should Be <br> Aware Of For 2025?</em></h4>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>Stormwater pollution trends 2025 will likely see increased focus on microplastics, pharmaceutical residues,
                and emerging contaminants. Climate change is also expected to exacerbate pollution issues through more intense rainfall events.</em>
              </p>
              <h4 class="text-center text-decoration-underline text-light" ><em>What Are Some Simple, Easy Tips <br> For Improving Drainage Quality At Home?</em></h4>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>Easy tips for drainage quality include regularly clearing gutters and downspouts of leaves and debris,
                ensuring downspouts direct water away from foundations and into permeable areas or rain barrels, and avoiding dumping anything down storm drains.</em>
              </p>
              <img src="images/preventImg8.jpg" alt="preventIMg8">
              <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-3 mt-1 pr-3"><em><u>Quality Control Measures for Pollution Mitigation</u></em></p>
              <hr>        
              <h4 class="text-center text-decoration-underline text-light" ><em><strong>Implementation Framework For <br>Effective Drainage QC</strong></em></h4>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>Successful implementation of these effective drainage QC measures requires a coordinated effort involving various stakeholders.</em></p>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em><strong>1.&emsp; <u>Regulatory Enforcement:</u></strong>&ensp; Strengthened monitoring by agencies like NESREA, potentially utilizing real-time effluent sensors, can ensure compliance with discharge standards [3][4]. Proper enforcement is critical for environmental regulations to be effective.</em></p>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em><strong>2.&emsp;<u>Industry Compliance:</u></strong> &ensp;High-risk sectors, such as automobile workshops and manufacturing facilities, must be mandated to install and maintain appropriate pretreatment systems to manage their specific pollutant loads [1][6]. This is a vital component of stormwater pollution control Nigeria.</em></p>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em><strong>3.&emsp; <u>Public-Private Partnerships:</u></strong> &ensp;Collaborative funding models can support the development and maintenance of decentralized filtration units, particularly in flood-prone urban areas. These partnerships can foster innovation and ensure the long-term sustainability of stormwater management Nigeria initiatives.</em></p>
              <p class="lead text-start text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em><strong>4.&emsp;<u> Public Awareness And Education:</u></strong>&ensp; Educating the public on the impacts of <strong>stormwater pollution</strong> and promoting responsible waste disposal practices are vital for collective action towards water safety tips Nigeria.</em></p>
              <p class="lead text-center text-light pl-4 pr-4"><em>By adopting these comprehensive QC measures, Nigeria can significantly reduce stormwater pollution, moving towards the water pollution prevention 2025 goals and aligning with global targets like Sustainable Development Goal 6 (Clean Water and Sanitation). This integrated approach will not only protect the environment but also enhance the resilience of urban areas against flooding, ensuring better urban water safety for all.</em></p>
